Associate Editor and multiple award winning journalist with The Nation, Olatunji Ololade, has made it to the final shortlist for the 2021 Fetisov Journalism Awards Outstanding Contribution to Peace category. Ololade’s entry: “The boys who swapped football for bullets – https://thenationonlineng.net/the-boys-who-swapped-football-for-bullets/“ is among the 13 entries shortlisted across 80 countries. Others shortlisted in the category are: Ali Al Ibrahim, Khalifa Al Khuder (Sweden / Syria): Syria’s Sinister Yet Lucrative Trade in Dead Bodies; Haris Rovčanin, Albina Sorguč (Bosnia and Herzegovina) — Series: BIRN Fact-Check: Is the Bosnian Serb Report on the Sarajevo Siege Accurate?   Motorists shun FCT elections to queue for fuel     CJN throws open Supreme Court Justice job to lawyers     Makinde to name new Olubadan on Monday   In an announcement by the organisers, the 13 entries which made it to the final shortlist selected from around 400 entries, will share a prize fund of 520,000 CHF, around 500,000 Euro. - Advertisement - Of the 13 winners, the first, second and third will be revealed at the award ceremony to be held at a gala event in Zurich on April 22. The organisers disclosed that the original list of entries from 80 countries was whittled down by the Fetisov Journalism Awards Expert Council who selected the 37 of them for the first shortlist and from this the FJA international Jury chose the 13 finalists. Ololade is a recipient of over 30 awards for journalism excellence spanning different categories of the CNN/Multichoice African Journalist Award, WAMECA, Wole Soyinka Prize for Investigative Journalism, Diamond Awards for Media Excellence (DAME), UN/Migration Reporting Awards, Rotary Humanitarian Journalism Awards and the Nigerian Media Merit Award (NMMA). SPONSORED